ChatGPT said:

Here is the clear and professional guidance on when to use <pre> and when to use white-space: pre-wrap. This is exactly how developers decide which one to use.

1. Use <pre> when:
You want the text to look EXACTLY like raw source text

Keeps all spaces, tabs, newlines

Uses a monospace font by default

Browser treats it like a “block of raw text”

Best for:

Code blocks

Logs

ASCII art

Configuration snippets

Example:
<pre>
function test() {
    console.log("Hello World");
}
</pre>


You get:

Fixed-width font

Exact indentation

Spaces preserved

2. Use white-space: pre-wrap when:
You want spaces + line breaks preserved BUT want normal styling

Uses your normal font, not monospace

Text wraps to next line (pre does not wrap)

You can style it normally

Best for:

Chat messages

User-entered notes

Paragraphs where spacing matters

Any formatted text in a UI

Example:
<div style="white-space: pre-wrap;">
Hello     this    keeps      the   spaces
but wraps normally and uses your site's font.
</div>

Quick Decision Guide
Need	Use
Preserve all spaces and newlines	<pre>
Show code/logs with fixed-width text	<pre>
Preserve spaces but keep normal font	white-space: pre-wrap;
Want long lines to wrap automatically	pre-wrap
Want full CSS control	pre-wrap
Which should YOU use most of the time?

For modern web apps (React, Next.js), the recommended approach is:

Use white-space: pre-wrap
Because it works well with normal fonts and responsive layouts.